column6: Family Home away from Home in Wpg
column7:
Full large 5 bed, 3 bedroom apartment in the lower level of My home. Fully furnished with all amenities featuring dishwasher, fireplace , well lit large kitchen , internet, smart 42" TV and Netflix .
Convenient Central Location & interesting well traveled host

The space
Full 5 bed, 3 bedroom apartment in the lower level of my home. One bedroom has a queen bed and a twin bed. Another bedroom has a double bed and a twin bed. The third one has a queen with a roll away bed (6th bed). It is a cozy 1100 square feet apt.
fully furnished with all amenities- dishwasher - blender - electric Fireplace (heater), microwave, coffee maker, toaster etc. All bedrooms are private with keyed locks. Large and well lit kitchen with 2 windows. Location is central, close to downtown and major bus routes!
-2 children s parks within 1 block
-one short block to sheltered bus stop and 3 blocks from Rapid Transit stop
-wireless internet, smart TV with c
column8:
Mainly I am surrounded by good neighbours and you are within walking distance to the popular Osborne Village, Corydon patio restaurant lined street and The Forks.
- Bus transportation is a block away. ;
- taxi rides to most areas $10 to $15. If you are a 3 or more it is cheaper then the Bus.
- short walk to restaurants, coffee shops, grocery store and gyms
- Bike trails bikes available
column15:
I am  Canadian. I was born in Belgium to Italian parents from Abruzzi Italia. I am 66 years old, an electrical engineer now retired with 4 children and 6 grandchildren. I have many relatives in Rome and Abruzzi. I go to Italy every 2 years, usually in August, for the festivals and to visit family but not anymore; too hot! October now! I have many relatives that live in Rome and Abruzzi. I had an uncle in Rome who passed in 2016 at 107. 

Mexico is my second home. Mazatlan and Puerto Vallarta are my main destinations for Mexico . I spend one month there in Nov and 1 month in March. Most of my time is spent mainly in Mazatlan, where I own a condo,  to play tennis and then about  5 days in Puerto Vallarta to Salsa dance. It is the dolce Vita ( sweet life) ,sunny and day time temps of about +28.

I  enjoy hosting on Airbnb mainly because I like meeting new people and having people come from around the world. I use Airbnb whenever I can for traveling around the world because it is so affordable.   Dom and his wife Jessica live close by my home and are co hosts with my airbnb. 

Silvio

column8: This charming neighbourhood is a bustling area of excitement and one of the most intact pre-1930 residential areas in Canada. Affectionately known as "The Granola Belt" of Winnipeg, Wolseley is a neighbourhood in tune with Mother Nature. Here you will find an organic bakery, bookstore, fair-trade coffee shop, organic grocery store and handmade perfumery. Omand Park is a unique green space on the cusp of Wolseley, where you’ll also find Omand’s Creek.

column15:
Hello Everyone,

I am an independent professional woman, a humanitarian at heart.

I was raised on a family farm in a rural community in Manitoba.  I am a specialty nurse and work in two WRHA hospitals in Winnipeg as an operating room nurse. I am a retired Canadian Forces nursing officer and am presently working with the International Operations of the Canadian Red Cross (Emergency Response Unit) in affiliation with the International Committee and International Federation of the Red Cross out of Geneva. Whenever the need arises, I am called to engage in medical humanitarian operations around the world with teams from many nations.

I am passionate about humanitarian work and have been on several missions/deployments around the world: Afghanistan, Honduras, Dominican Republic, South Sudan, South East Asia, Nepal, Iraq, Bangladesh etc.

I enjoy engaging in sports activities and dancing. I enjoy participating in fund raising events for several organizations along with my family and friends. 

I have been blessed with two wonderful children who are independent and very close to me.

We love to volunteer for special events around the city and local communities especially in the summer time. 

I enjoy hosting on Airbnb mainly because I like meeting new people, exchanging stories and experiences and having people visit from around the world. I use Airbnb, whenever available, for my visits to other nations because it is so affordable and they have very interesting and extremely helpful hosts.
 
I love to travel especially on adventure trips where I can hike, engage in white water rafting, zip lining etc. I also enjoy luxuries but prefer to mingle with locals to learn their culture through conversation and by listening to their stories. 

I enjoy cooking and making homemade foods, especially Ethnic & Mediterranean dishes. I also enjoy gardening and taking care of my yard to compliment the neighborhood.

Winnipeg is a highly spirited city. Just ask me!

Thank you.

Kindest Regards,
Dianne

column6: The Suite: Private Room + Kitchenette
column7:
The Suite at Chestnut Cottage is a cosy 2-room suite that sleeps 1 or 2 people with space to lounge/dine in the adjoining private kitchenette. We are minutes from downtown, in the friendly, walkable Wolseley neighbourhood.

RE: COVID-19 WE ARE VAXED/BOOSTED AND ASK THAT YOU BE, TOO. OUR ACCOMMODATIONS ARE NOT SUITABLE FOR SELF-ISOLATION/QUARANTINE. PLEASE MASK/SANITIZE FOR ENTRY/EXIT THROUGH SHARED SPACE.

The space
Located on the second floor of our circa 1908 home in the central Wolseley neighbourhood, The Suite features a sunny, east-facing 4-season sleeping porch with opening windows on three sides. The porch is furnished with a double brass bed, dresser and chair. In the adjoining kitchenette there is space to prepare and eat a light meal, lounge, watch movies or brush your teeth. At 17 m2 (180 sq ft), The Suite is ideal for solo travellers or couples. We are also open to longer-term guests including students, artists-in-residence, theatre folk, me
column8: Wolseley is a mixed neighbourhood of early 20th-century detached wood frame houses on elm-lined streets amid a scattering of small businesses and character apartment buildings. We are 5 minutes by bus or car, and less than 20 minutes on foot from downtown Winnipeg, the University of Winnipeg, Health Sciences Centre and Misericordia Health Centre. We are no more than 20 to 25 minutes by cab, bus or car from the University of Manitoba and most other destinations in the city. Several local grocery stores, coffee shops, bakeries, restaurants and other shops are within a 5-minute walk and major shopping is close by.
column15:
We are two women living in in a century home in the Wolseley neighbourhood, near downtown Winnipeg. One designer and one carpenter by trade, we love collaborating on the restoration of this old house, making it a home for ourselves and a restful home-away-from-home for travellers.

Recent travels have taken us to Paris, London, Liverpool, New York City and Chicago. Other times, we explore rural North America in our vintage 1959 Sprite Ariel British-built caravan.

Whether it is in our home or on the road, we hope to see you soon!

I surf, snowboard, bike and hike anywhere I can
I continue to backpack, revisiting places like India, Bali, Malaysia, Hawaii, Portugal, Sri Lanka, Morrocco repeatedly

Im happy to share my local and global knowledge specially if its over a glass of my wine!

column8:
Osborne St. South


Like it’s neighbour to the north, South Osborne is a groovy section of the city where cool kids congregate while, due to the abundance of families in its Riverview and Lord Roberts neighbourhoods, it also has a very cozy, friendly neighbourhood sort of feel.

The south part of Osborne Street cuts a line between these two neighbourhoods, which are some of the oldest residential areas of Winnipeg. Sandwiched between these abodes is a street chock full of fantastic casual eateries, along with The Park Theatre, arguably Winnipeg’s busiest venues for live music film and artsy happenings. Plus, South Osborne is where you can access the verdant, riverside parklands of Kingston Row

This walk-up summertime ice cream spot is just a short stroll from the pedestrian Elm Park Bridge and sees vast line-ups throughout the season.

In recent years, a handful of new shops and eateries have also opened in the area. At Chaeban Ice Cream, enjoy small batch, naturally made ice cream in incredible flavours like Abir Al Sham, a traditional Syrian recipe with rose water, orange blossom, toasted pistachios, ricotta cheese, and orchid root powder. column8:
Staying in the slower-paced East Exchange means an easy 15 minute walk along the tree-lined Red River to Old Saint-Boniface, the Forks, Shaw Stadium, and the Canadian Museum for Human Rights.

Saint-Boniface Hospital is a 20-25 minute walk over the Esplanade Riel and down Avenue Taché. Health Sciences Centre is a 20-25 minute walk down McDermot Avenue.

Equally close are MTS Centre, the Burton Cummings Theatre and the Metropolitan Theatre.

Winnipeg's modern business district, Portage & Main, is a 5 minute walk up Rorie Street.

Within the immediate vicinity of Le Loft 139 are the Royal MTS Theatre, the Warehouse Theatre, the Centennial Concert Hall, the Manitoba Museum and a plethora of restaurants, pubs, coffee shops, art galleries and boutiques.
column15:
On est un couple du même sexe originaire de Winnipeg, au Canada. Ensemble depuis vingt-cinq ans, on a habité en Suisse, en Espagne et au Canada.  On aime beaucoup cuisiner, mais en voyage on préfère dénicher des restaurants préparant des spécialités locales. Terre-à-terre, proches de nos familles, on apprécie tout particulièrement prendre un verre en compagnie de bons amis.


Quelques destinations ou voyages mémorables: le parc national Kruger et une bonne partie du reste de l'Afrique du Sud en self-drive; un voyage en cargo du Pirée (Grèce) jusqu'à Tanjung Pelepas (Malaisie) en passant par le canal de Suez, Jeddah (Arabie saoudite) et Colombo (Sri Lanka); Naples - une de nos villes préférées;  et la Jordanie en self-drive avec, comme cerise sur le sundae, une visite de la ville ancienne de Petra.  


We're a same-sex couple originally from Winnipeg, Canada. We've been together for over nearly 25 years and have lived in Switzerland, Spain and Canada. While we enjoy cooking when we are at home, we love going out to restaurants when we are on the road, trying new dishes and seeing how other people live and see the world. Down-to-earth and close to our families, we appreciate simple evenings sharing a good glass of wine with friends both new and old.

A few memorable trips: a self-drive safari in Kruger National Park (South Africa), sleeping under a star-filled sky in the Wadi Rum, Jordon, and a trip on the Hatsu Courage (a container ship) from Piraeus (Greece) to Tanjung Pelepas (Malaysia).  And, of course, Naples - one of our all-time favourite destinations.   While in Switzerland, we had the opportunity to travel to many European, North African and Middle Eastern destinations.

column8:
St. John's is one of the more established neighbourhoods of the North End, its development occurring shortly after the turn-of-the-century and being virtually complete by the mid-1920s. Residential structures pre-dating 1900 can be found on most streets in the neighbourhood. Churches, retail structures along Main Street, schools and other amenities have also been established through the years.
St. John's was part of the City of St. James when it became part of the City of Winnipeg which came into legal existence on January 1, 1972.
(taken from: the City of Winnipeg website)

In Winnipeg, Osborne Village is THE place to inhabit for today's young professionals.

Voted one of the best neighborhoods in Canada, Osborne Village is renowned for its strong urban character that includes an array of shops, turn of the century buildings, and diverse population.

With more than 8,000 inhabitants, Osborne Village has the most dense urban setting in Winnipeg and one of the most dense in western Canada making it a coveted, vibrant area which evokes a strong sense of ownership in its residents.

It is also well connected with many bus routes alongside Winnipeg's new and expanding bus rapid transit. Synergy One's location is further enhanced by it's setting off of the busier streets of Stradbrook and River ave, into the more private setting of Wardlaw Ave.

column8:
Tuxedo is Winnipeg’s “oh la la?area. Sprawling mansions, lush greenery and gorgeous character homes are found in this upscale suburban neighborhood. In the early 1900s Tuxedo was originally conceived as “Tuxedo Park,?an exclusive residential suburb.

Assiniboine Park is the area’s biggest attraction. This beautiful green space features a zoo, a duck pond, the Leo Mol Sculpture Garden, a new children's adventure playground area, Qualico Family Centre, trails, English gardens, restaurants, a pavilion and a stage for musical performances throughout the summer. The Park Café is warm, inviting and a picture-perfect place to have a meal with family and friends. Located inside the Qualico Family Centre, the child-friendly café is charming and affordable. If you want an up close and personal meeting with polar bears, then The Tundra Grill is sure to chill to the bone. This restaurant, located in the Assiniboine Park Zoo, offers exclusive views of playing polar bears while you dine.

column18: Winnipeg has been witness to a remarkable and continuing evolution: the transformation of its downtown area into a place to live and the place to be. From the pioneering success of the Forks, the state-of-the-art MTS Centre, the one-of-a-kind new Hydro Building, the iconic new Museum for Human Rights; the expanding University of Winnipeg developments and new Red River College campuses; to the vast array of arts and culture, clubs and restaurants that permeate the city's downtown and surrounding area. there is no shortage of places to go or activities to undertake. Scroll along beautifully landscaped waterside pathways and gardens, past new shops and waterfront condos…back through some of the city's finest preserved architecture and it is clear to see that there is almost an embarrassment of riches here…especially for a city as understated as this one is known to be.

column15:
My Airbnb adventures started in Gimli MB where I had 3 rental homes.  I enjoyed the many guests from all over the world.  People coming to fish, film makers, families and many dogs.  I have since sold these homes and have one airbnb location in Winnipeg.  The Riverview area in Winnipeg is so nice for walking, close to groceries library and coffee.  Great proximity to downtown Winnipeg and the Forks Market.  My home is pet friendly and has hosted many well behaved dogs. The Arnold house is old, built in the early 1900’s, fully insulated with some good triple pane new windows for nice air flow.  
The house is small with one small bedroom.  The living room has room for sleeping.  The house has good wifi and Bell Satelite TV.  The kitchen has a bit of everything.
The home has forced air natural gas heat and central air conditioning.  

The Riverview area was home for me since 1999.  I purchased and lived in 3 different Riverview homes over 20 years.  I owned many rental properties in the area that kept me busy.  I also purchased the old historic Park Theatre with my son’s  (Luke 17) father in 2004.  We turned the beautiful old Park Theatre into an event venue with good coffee and a place for neighbours to gather.  We rented DVD’s in our cafe and enjoyed watching our son grow up as we hosted gatherings from Weddings to music performances.  


I have recently moved and now live 15 minutes away on 2.5 acres with my teenage son and a lot of animals. We grow food and enjoy the great outdoors.  Thank you for finding our little house in Riverview.

Stroll along the beautiful landscaped walkway on Waterfront Drive, explore some of the finest preserved historic architecture, or simply relax in Stephen Juba Park which is just steps away from the loft.

within walking distance you will find the Manitoba Theatre Centre (right across the street!) column8:
St. John's is one of the more established neighbourhoods of the North End, its development occurring shortly after the turn-of-the-century and being virtually complete by the mid-1920s. Residential structures pre-dating 1900 can be found on most streets in the neighbourhood. Churches, retail structures along Main Street, schools and other amenities have also been established through the years.
St. John's was part of the City of St. James when it became part of the City of Winnipeg which came into legal existence on January 1, 1972.
(taken from: the City of Winnipeg website)

Our home is a bright, minimally-decorated detached house on a tree-lined street in a wonderful neighbourhood of Winnipeg.

The space
We love our clean, comfortable, lovely home! There is hardwood flooring throughout, white walls with artwork (I'm an artist), and big windows. The downstairs is mostly open-concept and though the house is not a big one, it has a spacious feel to it: the front sun room leads into the hallway/stairway, which leads into the combined living room and dining room. The kitchen and a mudroom for coats/shoes are at the back of the main floor.

Upstairs is the master bedroom, bathroom with full bath/shower, and a second bedroom/den, which has a comfortable futon with a foam top in it. Our home accommodates up to 4 adults/children.

Outside there's on-site parking for 1 vehicle, additional free parking on the street, a grassy front yard, a small front garden (a raised planter bed - help yourself to herbs and veggies!),
column8: The Corydon neighbourhood is a fantastic one!  You can easily and quickly walk to all the stores that you need (grocery, hardware, flower store etc), and also to a very special (arguably the best in town!) bakery, as well as a fantastic cheese shop, and my favourite restaurant in Winnipeg (as well as many other restaurants, bars etc).  There's a school around the corner from our house, and with that comes a nice neighbourly feel to the area - which is quiet and residential, but only 3 blocks away from a main restaurant/shopping area.  We're close to a river, parks and playgrounds, downtown and The Forks (10 minutes away by car), and main-route buses.

column8:
You’ve landed in Charleswood, the semi-rural community of forest trails and family-friendly eateries. Joggers, cyclists, and bird-watchers are abundant, as they embrace the combination of great places to eat with verdant greenery.

Here, you can hop on the Harte Trail, which runs for 6.5 km through an old railway bed and is part of the Trans Canada Trail, or stroll through Assiniboine Forest with 700 acres of wilderness and trails for exploring. After you’ve worked up an appetite, pop into Capital Grill and Bar where chef Wayne Martin offers an updated take on comfort food using Manitoba ingredients.

Bordering Charleswood is the can’t-miss attraction of Assiniboine Park. You can really spend your whole day here, as you watch polar bears swim overhead in the viewing tunnels of Journey to Churchill at the zoo, take the kids to the Assiniboine Park Nature Playground, enjoy a calm walk through the English Gardens while checking out the beautiful bronze sculptures at t

column8:
St. John's is one of the more established neighbourhoods of the North End, its development occurring shortly after the turn-of-the-century and being virtually complete by the mid-1920s. Residential structures pre-dating 1900 can be found on most streets in the neighbourhood. Churches, retail structures along Main Street, schools and other amenities have also been established through the years.
St. John's was part of the City of St. James when it became part of the City of Winnipeg which came into legal existence on January 1, 1972.
(taken from: the City of Winnipeg website)

Check out our extensive guidebook (see other listing: "Cozy Bungalow - Great Locations!") for info on nearby (and not-so-nearby) places to check out during your stay!

column8:
There are over 50 unique restaurants for your taste buds to explore in Winnipeg’s historic Exchange District.

The Exchange offers a culinary experience like no other. Check out some of Winnipeg’s most popular restaurants, bars and cafes that take pride in sourcing local ingredients, feature high quality creations and are innovative in their presentation.

Take a walk through the Exchange today and explore the immaculate architecture and delectable flavours of this world-class urban dining experience.

A feast for the eyes and the palate, the Exchange is an unforgettable dining experience, all within 30-square-blocks.

It’s nearly impossible to walk around the Exchange District and not feel transported to another time. The century-old architecture lays the groundwork for a community that is at once charming in its quaint, old-world familiarity, and innovative and bold, with an eye to the future.

column8:
Rich in history Point Douglas is one of Winnipegs earliest settlements. Barber house, Ross house Museum are both open for viewing in summer months.

This home offers significant history in itself. Situated in Winnipeg's first and only red-light district 1909-1912 and Purchased from the original family, this home was converted from a brothel, turned rooming house, duplex and now single family home.

*house is not haunted. Smudged by indigenous elder and blessed by a Christian minister*

Today North Point Douglas is a very diverse and rapidly changing neighborhood. Strong in activism, arts and indigenous culture the area has slowly battled a losing fight against gentrification. Surrounded on 3 sides by the red rier this neighbourhood offers beautiful views and easy accessibility to all the great things Winnipeg offers.

Only a few minute drive to The Forks/Human Rights Museum to fulfill your sightseeing needs. Or if you're feeling up to it, it's

In Winnipeg, Osborne Village is THE place to inhabit for today's young professionals.

Voted one of the best neighborhoods in Canada, Osborne Village is renowned for its strong urban character that includes an array of shops, turn of the century buildings, and diverse population.

With more than 8,000 inhabitants, Osborne Village has the most dense urban setting in Winnipeg and one of the most dense in western Canada making it a coveted, vibrant area which evokes a strong sense of ownership in its residents.

It is also well connected with many bus routes alongside Winnipeg's new and expanding bus rapid transit. Synergy One's location is further enhanced by it's setting off of the busier streets of Stradbrook and River ave, into the more private setting of Wardlaw Ave.

column8:
In Winnipeg, Osborne Village is THE place to inhabit for today's young professionals.

Voted one of the best neighborhoods in Canada, Osborne Village is renowned for its strong urban character that includes an array of shops, turn of the century buildings, and diverse population.

With more than 8,000 inhabitants, Osborne Village has the most dense urban setting in Winnipeg and one of the most dense in western Canada making it a coveted, vibrant area which evokes a strong sense of ownership in its residents.

It is also well connected with many bus routes alongside Winnipeg's new and expanding bus rapid transit. Synergy One's location is further enhanced by it's setting off of the busier streets of Stradbrook and River ave, into the more private setting of Wardlaw Ave.

column6: Minimalist Suite Central Location
column7:
Welcome to our minimalist, cosy space. Located in charming Wolseley, we’re close to restaurants, pubs, & coffee shops within walking distance. Ideal for people who like things simple, clean & practical. It is a private basement unit with a separate entry, pretty pot lights brighten up the room (only one window) & it has a small kitchenette; microwave/sink/kettle/cutlery/dishes. Rain shower head & heated bathroom floors. Laundry with $fee.

Please note:
Puppy in upper suite. May hear barking.

The space
Our space is unique because while it is a basement suite it is well lit, and has some key features that will make your stay very enjoyable. There is one double bed, and an additional futon that can be used for sleeping. A few of these are the heated floors in the bathroom, the rain showerhead, the private entrance as well as the utility of the space, layout and design. We want guests to feel comfortable in a clean, modern and practical space.
<
column8:
Our neighbourhood is known as Wolseley and it is unique because it is full of people who love the outdoors, including winter biking, hiking, outdoor running, or walking their dogs. Many families, students as well as professionals live around the neighbourhood so you may see people enjoying the neighbourhood by visiting the nearby cafes, supporting local businesses. You will find grocery stores such as Organic Planet where you can find more health and natural type of groceries as well as smaller grocery stores that also sell local products!

You may see posters promoting music, bands and theatre performances which is very common and older churches around the neighbourhood with beautiful architecture. We are also close to West Broadway which is where the majority of businesses and shops can be found by walking over!
column15:
My name is Bel and I love traveling and recently spent one year backpacking through Central and South America, Western Europe and South East Asia, and have been to over 25 countries. I really enjoy meeting new people and although Winnipeg is small I love introducing people to what this great city has to offer. 

I have had the chance to live in Sydney, Australia, Thailand, Mexico and has visited different parts of Western Europe and has traveled throughout Canada.  

I live in a central location and would love to help you enjoy your time in Winnipeg!

column8: 300 Assiniboine is situated in a park like setting along the banks of the Assiniboine River. If you love nice patios and al fresco dining, gelato, and an all round jovial atmosphere, then Corydon Avenue is for you. Once known as Winnipeg’s “Little Italy,?Corydon Ave is a destination district, one which is popular with visitors and locals alike for people watching, shopping and dining.

A vast array of cuisines are available ?from Japanese ramen, to Korean BBQ, to locally-sourced burgers, to sushi ?while classic Italiano institutions serving gelati and strong shots of espresso are evident throughout. It’s also still the neighbourhood to go watch Italy play, should the World Cup or Euros be on.

Corydon is also quite the shopping destination as trés chic shops now populate the avenue featuring everything from on-trend clothing stores to jewellery, while it has also become a popular salon and nail bar spot.

The area’s vibe is certainly artsy, as was recently emphasized Corydon Avenue Biz’s “street scaping.?The Colours of Corydon features eight h

column8:
Rich in history Point Douglas is one of Winnipeg's earliest settlements. Barber house, Ross house Museum are both open for viewing in summer months.

This home offers significant history in itself. Situated in Winnipeg's first and only legal red-light district 1909-1912, this home was converted from what was once one of Winnipeg's most prominent brothels.

*house is not haunted. Smudged by indigenous elder and blessed by a Christian minister*

Today North Point Douglas is a very diverse and rapidly changing neighborhood. Strong in activism, arts and indigenous culture the area has slowly battled a losing fight against gentrification. Surrounded on 3 sides by the red river this neighbourhood offers beautiful views and easy accessibility to all the great things Winnipeg offers.

column6: Cozy Bungalow Suite
column7:
Our bungalow is located in a residential area bounded by the river on 3 sides, and Osborne street thoroughfare on the west side. A 12 minute walk brings you to Osborne with grocery stores and restaurants. A 5 minute walk takes you to the river and a park with walks and bike trails which stretch to the forks on one side and to the BDI's ice cream on the other.
We love to meet new people. Both of us have received all available vaccinations for COVID and we ask the same of our non smoking guests.

The space
Essentially your part of the space would be a private 'basement suite' which is entered by using a private side entrance. It contains 2 bedrooms (1 queen bed and 1 bunk bed), a 'living room' area with 4 electric recliner seats, a large TV complete with Netflix access (actually a gaming console and DVD as well). You also have a full bathroom (shower, toilet and sink). There is a kitchenette area where you have a fridge, microwave, toaster oven, keurig coffee
column8: Churchill Park is close by and makes for some wonderful walks through market gardens,and to our favorite ice cream shop. Fisher Park , a block of green is a block away as is our community center with tennis courts, outdoor BB courts etc.
column15: I'm a retired computer science teacher who still dabbles in that field...working part time for my son's web design business. I enjoy classical music, sing in our church choir, travel south for the winter, jog enough to enter half marathons now and then and love taking my 1800 Goldwing out on the road. I met the love of my life, my Dutch born wife, in The Netherlands while volunteering for Youth for Christ. We both enjoy visiting Europe and especially Holland...even after having been there more than a dozen times.

column6: Large bedroom in North River Heights
column7:
Our house is located in beautiful River Heights, a quiet and friendly neighbourhood with lots of shopping and dining places. We are close to major bus routes - to downtown, both universities, local museums and other attractions. Nearby are Assiniboine Park & Zoo, only 5 minutes driving to Polo Park Shopping Mall, and 10 minutes driving from our house to The Forks, Canadian Museum for Human Rights, Manitoba Children's Museum, and more. We are less than 10 minutes driving to and from the airport.

The space
A cozy bedroom with one double bed, closet, desk, and dresser, located on the second floor in our house. Shared bathroom is located on the same level. Our guests enjoy free Wi-Fi, access to the living room, kitchen, dining area, and laundry area (washer / dryer). The house has central heating and A/C. We have an older dog who is friendly and non shedding.
column8: Welcome to River Heights, where elm trees line each street. Our house is within 5 minutes walking to the neighbourhood Starbucks, and to Bernstein's Deli that serves all-day breakfasts. Stella's Cafe on Grant is one of our favourite places for breakfast, lunch and dinner (5-minute drive).

column6: Historic Home in Great Location
column7:
A character home on one of the best blocks in the historic Wolseley neighborhood. All the original oak woodwork and 2 enclosed outdoor porches. Steps away from public transit (10 minutes to downtown Winnipeg) Organic bakery, convenience store and book store one block away. Restaurants, pubs and outdoor patios a short walk away. Human Rights Museum is a 10-15 minute drive or a short taxi ride away. I have lived in Winnipeg all my life so we have lots of recommendations for your stay.

The space
I am a filmmaker and tv host so this house has a lot of good creative energy. I have written many award winning films in this house. A great place to write and think late at night! We are usually up late so don't worry about coming in at a late hour!

Guest access
We have a 3rd floor office with another computer(internet access) for you to use if you want to get work done. In the summer, enjoy our back deck with a bbq.

column8: Our neighborhood is full of Victorian Homes built around the turn the century.    The tall grass prairie bakery is just down the street and has the best wholewheat cinnamon buns and  the chocolate brownies are dense and delicious!!   Paradise restaurant is a 10 minute walk away and has the best Italian pasta and pizza around!   Tell Mary and Kim I sent you!
column15: Hi, I am a television producer/host.  I started my career as a television reporter for the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation.  I now host/produce a series called, "Vitality Gardening" which can be seen on FNX in the U.S.   My passion is making documentaries and I am in post production on a project right now :)   The love of my life is Wayne and he is pretty funny...always makes me laugh.  Wayne is a former politician who now works as a server at a restaurant while he contemplates his next career move.  We have a rescue dog..a minature schnauzer named Charlie and we just love him to bits!!   As guests, we are quiet and respectful.   We both love Italian food...I could not live without coffee...Wayne could not live without laughter.   We have never stayed at an Airbnb before...but we are very responsible and and love exploring new places.   My life motto is Always Follow your dreams.

column15:
Alex is the owner of Travel To Discover. An experience based tour company, which aims to connect local businesses and communities with everyone.

"Travel To Discover" is a product of my passion for sustainable tourism and bridging the gaps between the communities and tourists. 

During my extensive globe trotting experience I always yearned to be involved in the real culture and taste it. And I think every adventure seeker like me should experience it. Travel To Discover is passionate about travelling just like you.!!!

column8:
St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

column8:
Our fully furnished bungalow is located in a quiet residential area bounded by the river on 3 sides, and Osborne street thoroughfare on the west side. A 12 minute walk brings you to Osborne with grocery stores and restaurants. A 5 minute walk takes you to the river and a park with walks cross country ski trails. Their is usually a skating path all the way to the forks on the river. A 3 minute walk brings you to a bus stop.
Churchill Park is close by and makes for some wonderful walks through market gardens,and to our favorite ice cream shop. Fisher Park , a block of green is a block away as is our community center with tennis courts, outdoor BB courts etc.

column11:
Winnipeg's Exchange District is one of the most iconic and vibrant neighborhoods in Winnipeg. This national historic site features an exceptional collection of heritage buildings built between 1880 and 1920. Nicknamed the “Chicago of the North? the Exchange features more than 150 immaculate heritage buildings within 20-square-blocks. These buildings and tree-lined streets, which were once warehouses and “terra cotta skyscrapers?that housed financial institutions, have since become Winnipeg’s cultural hub, blanketed with restaurants, galleries, gourmet donut and coffee shops, hip clothing, lifestyle and design stores.

Our loft, in the heart of the Exchange District, is steps away from the river, with a beautiful walking & biking trail. This area is a walker's paradise. Stroll along the river for 10 minutes to the Goldeye's Shaw Park and 10 minutes more to The Forks and The Canadian National Human Rights Museum. A 2-minute walk in the other direction takes you into the Thea
column15: Martina, Bruce, And Lauren
column18:
" We travel the world over in search of what we need and return home to find it" 

As a little girl, I always admired the way a space and its?contents have the ability to create memories and feelings. One of my earliest realizations of that experience was when my family and I spend a Christmas at a refugee camp when I was 10 years old. We had just escaped communism, leaving everything behind, yet my parents managed to create for us a lovely corner in our room with a small decorated Christmas tree, a bowl of nuts, some Mandarins, and even a few small presents. I still remember wondering how they managed to put this together for my sister and me? It was the loveliest feeling and that wonderful memory is still vivid in my mind as one of my very favorite Christmases. 

Perhaps it is this experience in leaving our life and all our worldly possessions behind to start again, which makes me always pause in a space and take in how it makes me feel. I truly believe in the wonder and emotional connection to the things that we choose to surround ourselves with. 

I have also been fortunate to put my head down on a pillow in many lovely places during my 20 years of executive global travel. I have come to appreciate that there are a few essentials that have always put a smile on my face and made me feel at home while traveling away from home. It is with this mindset that my family and I have approached the creation of this loft, our special space. 

A beautifully-appointed loft, with comfy bedding and linens, lovely amenities, all the comforts of home, and an opportunity to connect with locals, are but a few of the things that we hope our home and family can offer. We are passionate about our city and would love to share everything that may be of interest to you about Winnipeg. There is so much to discover and talk about in English, French, or Czech if you prefer.
We look forward to meeting you.

My wife and I enjoy travelling and seeing new things. But, what we enjoy most about travelling doesn't involve visiting the tourist traps. We like to do what the locals do in their town while being able to relax in a comfortable space at the end of the day. An affinity for clean, colourful and fun design,  good eats, great music (jazz, hip-hop and R&B), great entertainment (on the street or in a theatre or stadium) and reading anything by an interesting person with life lessons to share.

Life Motto? Anything worth doing is worth doing well. Live well, travel well and do right by treating our guests well.

Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

You can’t mention downtown without talking about Bell MTS Place, which is the home of both our NHL team, the Winnipeg Jets, and our AHL team, the Manitoba Moose. Bell MTS Place is a

column7:
Centrally located in prestigious River Heights on a tree-lined quiet street. Our home boasts many quiet, private comfortable rooms. Exceptional outdoor space with fenced in, extra deep backyard that is kid and dog-friendly (sorry, no cats due to allergies). Proximity to great restaurants, recreational facilities, biking/walking trails and Winnipeg's best shopping. Public transit options only steps away. Perfect for families, couples or business stays. Lots of free parking.

The space
The house served as our cozy family home and now you are invited to relax here too. Each of the 3 bedrooms have areas for sitting and reading as well as lots of space for your things. The secluded basement has it's own full bathroom, living room, big screen TV, sitting/reading area and comfortable bedroom. Turquoise accents throughout were inspired by our love for the waters of Mexico. The recently remodeled chef-style kitchen has the feel of a beach house. The living room wit
column8: River Heights is one of the most prestigious neighbourhoods in Winnipeg and this house is situated dead centre of where the best amenities are located.  Exceptional dining options are literally steps away - highlighted by Enoteca, ranked as one of Canada's top 100 restaurants 1.5 blocks away. Fusion Grill, Pizzeria Gusto, Leopold's Tavern, Mona Lisa Restaurante and Starbucks can all be reached by walking.  Wellington Crescent 2 blocks down has Winnipeg's most luxurious homes and it's boulevard-style street following the Assiniboine River is a popular walking, running and cycling route.  The street flows right into Assiniboine Park, Winnipeg's "city park" home to world renowned Zoo, outdoor theatre and enormous green space.  Shopping enthusiasts will be amazed at the proximity to Polo Park (7 minutes), Ikea, Cabellas and the newest Premium Outlet Collection mall (10 minutes).  We are surrounded by recreational facilities including a children's wading pool, play structure and community c
column15: My wife Kathryne is a Food and Travel writer so of course we love to travel but we also are very attached to our hometown of Winnipeg.   Winnipeg is full of friendly, down-to-Earth hard working people that care for each other.  Since we share our time between our lovely home in River Heights and our lake cottage on Lake Winnipeg, we thought we would start to invite others to our comfortable and inviting home.  You can be one of the first to experience where much of our joy comes from.  Our neighbourhood is second to none with so much to do so close by.

RE: COVID-19 - WE ARE VAXED/BOOSTED AND ASK THAT YOU BE, TOO. OUR ACCOMMODATIONS ARE NOT SUITABLE FOR SELF-ISOLATION/QUARANTINE. PLEASE MASK/SANITIZE FOR ENTRY/EXIT THROUGH SHARED SPACE.

The space
Lost behind a baseboard for over a century, lay a Valentine postcard to Miss Gracie Portman, with love from Norma, posted February 13, 1917 in Billings, Montana.

Stay in Gracie's room, located on the second floor of our circa 1908 home in the central Wolseley neighbourhood. Your room features a queen size bed, reading nook, dining/work table and a dry mini-kitchenette. The room is ideal for solo travellers or couples.

Guest access
column8: Wolseley is a mixed neighbourhood of early 20th-century detached wood frame houses on elm-lined streets amid a scattering of small businesses and character apartment buildings. We are 5 minutes by bus or car, and less than 20 minutes on foot from downtown Winnipeg, the University of Winnipeg, Health Sciences Centre and Misericordia Health Centre. We are no more than 20 to 25 minutes by cab, bus or car from the University of Manitoba and most other destinations in the city. Several local grocery stores, coffee shops, bakeries, restaurants and other shops are within a 5-minute walk and major shopping is close by.
column15:
We are two women living in in a century home in the Wolseley neighbourhood, near downtown Winnipeg. One designer and one carpenter by trade, we love collaborating on the restoration of this old house, making it a home for ourselves and a restful home-away-from-home for travellers.

Recent travels have taken us to Paris, London, Liverpool, New York City and Chicago. Other times, we explore rural North America in our vintage 1959 Sprite Ariel British-built caravan.

Whether it is in our home or on the road, we hope to see you soon!

You will be staying in North River Heights steps from Academy Street, Wellington Cres. and numerous local shops/restaurants. Central to many things, yet private in its location. This neighborhood is known for its friendly community and desirable, safe central location. I'd venture to say, it's one of if not the most affluent neighborhoods in the city. It's definitely my favourite :)

The outlet mall is new this year and within a 5 minute drive to the south. Right next to the new mall is IKEA, plus many more shops and restaurants. Both are well worth checking out!

For breakfast, Stella's is less than a kilometer away, just north at Grant & Kenaston. Pizzeria Gusto is literally down the blocks, offering amazing wood fired pizzas, and a one of the best patios in town.

Head further north approximately 5 minutes, and you are now nearing the St. James area and Polo Park which has arguably the best shopping in the city.

In Winnipeg, Osborne Village is THE place to inhabit for today's young professionals.

Voted one of the best neighborhoods in Canada, Osborne Village is renowned for its strong urban character that includes an array of shops, turn of the century buildings, and diverse population.

With more than 8,000 inhabitants, Osborne Village has the most dense urban setting in Winnipeg and one of the most dense in western Canada making it a coveted, vibrant area which evokes a strong sense of ownership in its residents.

It is also well connected with many bus routes alongside Winnipeg's new and expanding bus rapid transit.

column8:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

You can’t mention downtown without talking about Bell MTS Place, which is the home of both our NHL team, the Winnipeg Jets, and our AHL team, the Manitoba Moose. Bell MTS Place is a

column8:
Rich in history Point Douglas is one of Winnipeg's earliest settlements. Barber house, Ross house Museum are both open for viewing in summer months.

This home offers significant history in itself. Situated in Winnipeg's first and only red-light district 1909-1912 and Purchased from the original family, this home was converted from a brothel, turned rooming house, duplex and now single family home.

*house is not haunted. Smudged by indigenous elder and blessed by a Christian minister*

Today North Point Douglas is a very diverse and rapidly changing neighborhood. Strong in activism, arts and indigenous culture the area has slowly battled a losing fight against gentrification. Surrounded on 3 sides by the red river this neighbourhood offers beautiful views and easy accessibility to all the great things Winnipeg offers.

Only a few minute drive to The Forks/Human Rights Museum to fulfill your sightseeing needs. Or if you're feeling up to it, it's

column8:
If you love nice patios, al fresco dining, gelato, and an all round jovial atmosphere, then Corydon Avenue is for you. Once known as Winnipeg’s “Little Italy,?Corydon Ave is a destination district, one which is popular with visitors and locals alike for people watching, shopping and dining. In the summer, you’ll find shady patios packed with people sipping sangria and beer. On Friday and Saturday nights during July and August, you’ll find a live music during the “Dancing on the Avenue?concert series featuring everything from 50s rock to jazz to blues.

A vast array of cuisines is available ?from Japanese ramen, to Korean BBQ, to locally-sourced burgers, to sushi ?while classic Italiano institutions serving gelati and strong shots of espresso are evident throughout. It’s also still the neighbourhood to go watch European sports, should the World Cup or Euros be on.

Corydon is also quite the shopping destination as trés chic shops now populate the avenue featurin

column6: Historical Winnipeg in the Perfect Location
column7:
Traditional Townhouse Reconstruction of Winnipeg's industrial era in the Heart of Old St. Boniface.

Master Bedroom with ensuite on the 3rd floor. The second floor is the 2nd Bedroom with Full over Queen Bunk & family room with Queen sofa bed. The main floor living room surrounds the wood burning fire place. Walkscore of 79. Situated on a Park overlooking the Red River and the Historic Forks Market. Nestled between St. Boniface's Hospital , Museum and University.

The space

This brand new building offers a private entrance and separate garage parking. The Kitchen and bathrooms are fully stocked and well appointed. We are fully equipped for your stay with WiFi & and SMART TV.

Large feature windows with rare antique stained glass, beautiful grand high ceilings and original hardwood floors, this 3 story character home will charm you with many original touches true to its era blended with an updated kitchen and large open dining and living area.

This is a great option with plenty of space for families or small groups.

You'll be just steps from the Corydon Avenue restaurant, shops and patios.

The space
This home features 3 floors, 4 bedrooms + den and 2 bathrooms.

On the main floor there is:
-A fully equipped kitchen stocked with a full sized refrigerator/freezer, cookware, plates, utensils, toaster, microwave and electric stove/oven.

-Dining/living room

The lower level has an unfinished basement with a full bathroom and shower stall.

The 2nd floor features:
- 1 bedroom with 1 queen bed
- 2 bedrooms with 1 double bed
- 1 full bathroom
- Laun
column8:
Explore the neighbourhood's popular Corydon Avenue which has a small-town European charm. Step into one of the many family-owned cafés, boutiques and bakeries (don't forget to check out our guide for a list of personal favourites). The neighbourhood is a local favourite especially during summer, when Winnipeger's set out to enjoy the sunshine at its many street side or roof top patios.

Close and easy access to other great attractions like The Forks, and centrally located within the city making it easy to travel from one end of city to another.

column26:
The suburban neighbourhood of Norwood West consists almost entirely of residential properties. Nestled into a generous bend of the Red River, the area is home to many upscale riverfront properties and plentiful green space offers residents the chance to get out and enjoy nature. Shopping, dining, and entertainment opportunities are easily accessible in nearby Norwood East or downtown Winnipeg.

This picturesque riverfront community is made up of mostly single family homes, though renters can take advantage of a small number of apartments along St. Mary's Road. The peaceful ambiance and safe vibe of the area makes it a popular choice for professionals who enjoy being close to downtown but don't want the noise, crime, and congestion that can come with downtown living.

Active residents of all ages can enjoy year-round recreational activities at Norwood community centre. Baseball fields, ice-skating rinks, an outdoor pool, tennis courts and the Winnipeg Rowing Club pro

column8:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

You can’t mention downtown without talking about Bell MTS Place, which is the home of both our NHL team, the Winnipeg Jets, and our AHL team, the Manitoba Moose. Bell MTS Place is a

column8:
Elm Tree Place is centrally located in the quiet neighbourhood of Crescentwood under a canopy of century-old elm and oak trees. The house is located within walking distance of Corydon Avenue, a local favourite for food and drinks, as well as Academy Road, a great destination for boutique shopping. Crescentwood is known for its heritage homes and peaceful welcoming atmosphere.

Elm Tree Place is located on Treaty 1 Territory. We are committed to honouring this land as the traditional lands of the the Anishinaabeg, Inninewuk, Anishininiwag, Dakota Oyate, and Denesuline people, and the homeland of the Metis nation, 'as long as the river flows'.

Location

The heart of Winnipeg's French community, St. Boniface is a historic neighbourhood with lots to offer. From culturally rich food, to quaint cafes to artisanal chocolate shops - a food lover will not be disappointed with what this area has to offer. After a bite to eat stroll the popular Provencher Boulevard that leads up to the elegant and beautiful Provencher Bridge. This bridge connects St.Boniface to downtown Winnipeg. 

Steps away from our rental are two of Winnipeg's biggest attractions - the Canadian Museum for Human Rights (CMHR) and The Forks. The CMHR is an architectural marvel and one of it's kind in Canada. The Forks is located at the junction of the Red and Assiniboine Rivers. It is a large community hub that offers shopping, dining, and recreational activities year round.

In the heart of River Heights and a short drive to our very own "Little Italy" neighbourhood in Corydon where you are surrounded by great places to eat and drink. A 5 minute drive from both Polo Park Shopping Centre and The Outlet Collection Winnipeg!

Downtown and the Winnipeg Airport are a 10-15 minute drive away.

Corydon Avenue and Osborne Village have a great patio vibe in the summer! We recommend Saffron's, Teo's and Carlos & Murphey's! There's also some fantastic coffee and dessert shops!

For families, Assiniboine Park Zoo is a MUST! There are many great animals to see and the Polar Bears make great entertainment! Take a stroll through Assiniboine Park afterwards, the duck pond is beautiful and there are plenty of walking paths and picnic spots. Only a 5 minute drive away!

column7:
In the heart of Osborne Village, one short block from Little Italy, and a skip to downtown and The Forks: you'll love our location. We have a soccer pitch, playground and ice rink right on our street.
When you're home, you'll enjoy the comfortable furniture and eclectic décor in our spacious 1400-square-foot, 4-bedroom + loft office and lounge + front porch home. We are well suited to families, so pull out board game, cozy up to a movie, or get some work done in the two home-office spaces.

The space
This is our beautiful, 116-year old family home. Here you will learn of my love affair with bright colour, chandeliers, locally hand-crafted works of art, and adoration of live houseplants.

My family and I recently moved just a few blocks away, leaving you our home, furniture, favourite family games, and even our vegetable harvest just for you.

Cook in our newly renovated kitchen, complete with gas stove and stove-top grill; brand n
column8:
Our license plates say "Friendly Manitoba" for a reason, and Osborne Village is the best place in Winnipeg to meet people!

Our home is located immediately behind an elementary school and community centre. You have a play structure, free public wading pool, outdoor ice skating rink, soccer pitch and lots of walking paths just outside your door.

We are just one block from Osborne street, where you will find nightclubs, pubs, restaurants, and trendy shops. We are also one block in the other direction from the beginning of the Corydon Avenue strip, known as Little Italy, where you will find a blend of both affordable and upscale restaurants and lounges. Indeed, within 10 minutes -on foot- of our front door, you will find over 50 restaurants.

Just a 15-minute walk away you will find the Assiniboine River. Directly on the other side is downtown Winnipeg. In the winter you can ski or skate right on the river for miles in either direction on groomed tr
column15:
Hello - I am a business owner, graduate student (public health), mother, and avid traveler (45 countries on 5 continents).  I love to integrate big city urban adventures with off-the-beaten-path excursions into nature.  I have never found a destination too hot, I love to cook for myself where I can, and have a passion for local food markets. 
When we aren’t camping on beaches or hiking in rainforests we are definitely at an AirBnB for our travel stays! 
My family and I recently moved a few blocks away from our eclectic, 116-year old family home. We are so excited to be new AirBnB hosts and integrate the many thoughtful and unique features we have found in other AirBnB’s into our home for you. Can’t wait to meet you in Winnipeg, or abroad!

*SAFETY and COVID-19*

Suite Stay Properties welcomes guests each day. We place the utmost importance on cleanliness and disinfection. We have rigorous cleaning protocols in place, which include the use of electrostatic sprayers for extra sanitation in all units and public spaces. Providing our guests with a safe and clean environment is our
column8:
Location

The heart of Winnipeg's French community, St. Boniface is a historic neighbourhood with lots to offer. From culturally rich food, to quaint cafes to artisanal chocolate shops - a food lover will not be disappointed with what this area has to offer. After a bite to eat stroll the popular Provencher Boulevard that leads up to the elegant and beautiful Provencher Bridge. This bridge connects St.Boniface to downtown Winnipeg.

Steps away from our rental are two of Winnipeg's biggest attractions - the Canadian Museum for Human Rights (CMHR) and The Forks. The CMHR is an architectural marvel and one of it's kind in Canada. The Forks is located at the junction of the Red and Assiniboine Rivers. It is a large community hub that offers shopping, dining, and recreational activities year round.
column15: Hi! We're Suite Stay Properties! We provide fully furnished rental accommodations in the beautiful city of Winnipeg, Manitoba. We are a locally based company. We currently own and manage over 80 properties throughout the city. Our suites are located in some of Winnipeg's most desirable areas with wonderful attractions nearby. If you're planning a stay in Winnipeg - we would love to host you!

column8: Wolseley is a mixed neighbourhood of early 20th-century detached wood frame houses on elm-lined streets amid a scattering of small businesses and character apartment buildings. We are 5 minutes by bus or car, and less than 20 minutes on foot from downtown Winnipeg, the University of Winnipeg, Health Sciences Centre and Misericordia Health Centre. We are no more than 20 to 25 minutes by cab, bus or car from the University of Manitoba and most other destinations in the city. Several local grocery stores, coffee shops, bakeries, restaurants and other shops are within a 5-minute walk and major shopping is close by.
column15:
We are two women living in in a century home in the Wolseley neighbourhood, near downtown Winnipeg. One designer and one carpenter by trade, we love collaborating on the restoration of this old house, making it a home for ourselves and a restful home-away-from-home for travellers.

Recent travels have taken us to Paris, London, Liverpool, New York City and Chicago. Other times, we explore rural North America in our vintage 1959 Sprite Ariel British-built caravan.

Whether it is in our home or on the road, we hope to see you soon!

column8: You will be staying in the west side of River Heights near the Tuxedo border. Central to many things, yet private in its location. This neighborhood is known for its friendly community and desirable, safe central location. I'd venture to say, it's one of if not the most affluent neighborhoods in the city. It's definitely my favorite :)  The outlet mall is new this year and within a 2 minute drive to the south. Right next to the new mall is IKEA. Both are well worth checking out!  For breakfast, Stella's is less than a kilometer away, just north at Grant & Kenaston - one of my favorite spots.  Head further north approximately 5 minutes, and you are now nearing the St. James area and Polo Park which has arguably the best shopping in the city.  Head east and follow Pembina Highway north to confusion corner, and in a total of ten minutes you will find yourself in the heart of Winnipeg's Little Italy with many great bars and restaurants.

column8:
Winnipeg's Exchange District is one of the most iconic and vibrant neighbourhoods in Winnipeg. This national historic site features an exceptional collection of heritage buildings built between 1880 and 1920. Nicknamed the “Chicago of the North? the Exchange features more than 150 immaculate heritage buildings within 20-square-blocks.

These buildings and tree-lined streets, which were once warehouses and “terra cotta skyscrapers?that housed financial institutions, have since become Winnipeg’s cultural hub, blanketed with restaurants, galleries, gourmet donut and coffee shops, hip clothing, lifestyle and design stores.

It’s also become the home to many Winnipeg businesses including graphic design and architecture firms, tech start-ups via Innovation Alley, and photography studios. Above the streets many of these older buildings?floors have been converted into stylish studio apartments where a lot of the city’s hip set have started to migrate.

column8: Downtown Winnipeg is an area of Winnipeg located near the confluence of the Red and Assiniboine rivers. It is the oldest urban area in Winnipeg, and is home to the city's commercial core, city hall, the seat of Manitoba's provincial government, and a number of major attractions and institutions. Neighbourhoods in the downtown area include the Exchange District, Central Park, The Forks, and Chinatown. The downtown area is roughly 3 square kilometres (740 acres). Winnipeg Square, Bell MTS Place, Portage Place, are all located on the downtown section of Portage Avenue. On Main Street are Winnipeg's City Hall, Union Station, and the Manitoba Centennial Centre, which includes the Manitoba Museum, the Planetarium, the Centennial Concert Hall, and the Winnipeg Railway Museum.

Suite Stay Properties welcomes guests each day. We place the utmost importance on cleanliness and disinfection. We have rigorous cleaning protocols in place, which include the use of electrostatic sprayers for extra sanitation in all units and public spaces. column8:
Location

The heart of Winnipeg's French community, St. Boniface is a historic neighbourhood with lots to offer. From culturally rich food, to quaint cafes to artisanal chocolate shops - a food lover will not be disappointed with what this area has to offer. After a bite to eat, stroll the popular Provencher Boulevard that leads up to the elegant and beautiful Provencher Bridge. This bridge connects St.Boniface to downtown Winnipeg.
Steps away from our rental are two of Winnipeg's biggest attractions - the Canadian Museum for Human Rights (CMHR) and The Forks. The CMHR is an architectural marvel and one of it's kind in Canada. The Forks is located at the junction of the Red and Assiniboine Rivers. It is a large community hub that offers shopping, dining, and recreational activities year round.

column15:
I've travelled to several Canadian destinations: Saltspring Island, Victoria, Vancouver, Calgary, Windsor, Toronto. London, Montreal, Quebec City, Halifax, and parts of Newfoundland. I also lived and worked in London, England for a year and travelled throughout Europe. Currently my husband and I live in a small town on the prairies, with frequent visits to Winnipeg. Prior to moving here, we spent several years living in London and Windsor, Ontario. I got into birding during the first lockdown and also love photography as a hobby. I work in marketing at a credit union and have a background in graphic design. My husband works as a nurse and as a musician (singer and guitar player). 

In the spring of 2013 we used air bnb for the first time on a visit to NYC. Since then we've used airbnb  extensively on trips including Glasgow, Edinburgh, Isle of Skye, Oban, Islay, Stockholm, Umea, Florence, Cinque Terre, Barcelona, Guatemala, Cuba, Mexico, and more!

column8:
St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

column8:
Winnipeg's Exchange District is one of the most iconic and vibrant neighbourhoods in Winnipeg. This national historic site features an exceptional collection of heritage buildings built between 1880 and 1920.
Nicknamed the “Chicago of the North? the Exchange features more than 150 immaculate heritage buildings within 20-square-blocks.

These buildings and tree-lined streets, which were once warehouses and “terra cotta skyscrapers? have since become Winnipeg’s cultural hub, blanketed with restaurants, galleries, gourmet donut and coffee shops, hip clothing, lifestyle and design stores.

It’s also become the home to many Winnipeg businesses including graphic design and architecture firms, tech start-ups and photography studios. Above the streets many of these older buildings?floors have been converted into stylish studio lofts, like this one.

Nearby acclaimed dining includes: Deer+Almond with a menu that has graced several of Canada’s best restauran

St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

column8:
St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

column8:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

You can’t mention downtown without talking about Bell MTS Place, which is the home of both our NHL team, the Winnipeg Jets, and our AHL team, the Manitoba Moose. Bell MTS Place is a

column6: in the heart of Corydon Village
column7: When it comes to shopping and dining, Corydon Avenue aka Little Italy is one of the top destinations in the city - non ci piove! Here, you will find an eclectic array of local eateries and boutiques. Whether you spend a morning, afternoon or evening, there's plenty to uncover down this popular strip.
column8:
If you love nice patios, al fresco dining, gelato, and an all round jovial atmosphere, then Corydon Avenue is for you. Once known as Winnipeg’s “Little Italy,?Corydon Ave is a destination district, one which is popular with visitors and locals alike for people watching, shopping and dining. In the summer, you’ll find shady patios packed with people sipping sangria and beer. On Friday and Saturday nights during July and August, you’ll find a live music during the “Dancing on the Avenue?concert series featuring everything from 50s rock to jazz to blues.

A vast array of cuisines is available ?from Japanese ramen, to Korean BBQ, to locally-sourced burgers, to sushi ?while classic Italiano institutions serving gelati and strong shots of espresso are evident throughout. It’s also still the neighbourhood to go watch European sports, should the World Cup or Euros be on.

Corydon is also quite the shopping destination as trés chic shops now populate the avenue featuring

column15:
My story 

As a child, I watched my mother host hundreds of visitors from all around the world. I would wonder why she would invite all these people at home for dinner, lunch or breakfast. Sometimes some would stay for a week, a month or just a few days.  My mother would go the extra mile to make sure all the guests felt at home. She was and still is the most wonderful host I ever known.

Now that I have grown, I understand that this is a natural gift that she had and took pride in. She found, still finds great satisfaction in it.

I started to join my mother in this beautiful adventure, and I started to fall in love with hosting guests with her. And now, it’s always a joy to host friends at my own house.

My siblings say that I love to serve people. And that can’t be far from the truth. 

I started thinking of being an Airbnb host since 2017. I even opened an account but as they say, God’s time is always the best. Last year , we decided to go all in with my husband.

For the few months, this has been the best adventure we both are on. So great to host incredible people who are visiting our beautiful city of Winnipeg. 

And as someone who travels and uses Airbnb in other cities, I knew exactly what guests love. We’ve made sure that when you stay at any of our properties, it’s a home away from home experience. 

We’ve gone above & beyond to make sure that when you book your stay with us, you’ll have the most memorable time. And you’ll have everything you need. 

So if you have friends or family visiting Winnipeg and they would love a place to stay, we would be happy to host them. 

We currently have 3 Short Term Rentals. And we are Now SUPERHOST .  View them and watch the virtual tour for the 2 of them.

I’m really excited to host you & your families.

column8:
St. Boniface is home to one of the largest francophone communities west of the Great Lakes, and it is the heart of Manitoba's French history and culture. While here, you can stroll along le boulevard Provencher and visit boutiques and quaint cafés along the way.

Gaining buzz in the French Quarter is Marion Street Eatery, which serves stylized comfort food for breakfast and lunch. Other notable eateries include: Resto Gare, where authentic French cuisine is served aboard a refurbished train car; Promenade Café and Wine with gorgeous views of The Forks and the downtown skyline; and Le Garage Café, which is constantly packed with live music lovers and is renown as one of the best poutines in the city.
Bookworms can head to À la Page for the largest selection of French books in the city, while chocolate lovers can satisfy a sweet-tooth at Chocolatier Constance Popp with artisan bon bons, bars, truffles, and more. Their chocolates make fantastic takeaway treats to give a

Nestled in one of Winnipeg's most mature neighborhood's and surrounded with things to do. Close to Corydon, Osborne Village, Polo Park Shopping Centre, Downtown and the Winnipeg Airport and surrounded by great places to eat and drink.

Corydon Avenue and Osborne Village have a great patio vibe in the summer and beautiful lights in the winter. We recommend Saffron's, Teo's and Carlos & Murphey's! There are also some fantastic coffee and dessert shops!

For families, Assiniboine Park Zoo is a MUST! There are many great animals to see and the polar bears make great entertainment! Take a stroll through Assiniboine Park afterwards, the duck pond is beautiful and there are plenty of walking paths and picnic spots!

column8: The Exchange District today thrives as one of Winnipeg's commercial and cultural centers, as home to an array of specialty retailers, restaurants, nightclubs, art galleries, wholesalers, and condos. The Exchange is home to the Manitoba Museum as well as the Planetarium and a Science Gallery.Winnipeg's theatre district is located on the east side of the Exchange District, home to the Manitoba Theatre Centre, and Centennial Concert Hall which houses the Winnipeg Symphony Orchestra, the Royal Winnipeg Ballet, and the Manitoba Opera. Old Market Square annually hosts the Jazz Winnipeg Festival, the Winnipeg Fringe Theatre Festival, and the Manitoba Electronic Music Exhibition. Its cobblestone streets and friendly pedestrian environment also contribute to The Exchange District's popularity as a period backdrop for the movie industry. column8: The suburban neighbourhood of Norwood East consists almost entirely of residential properties. Backing on community club, near schools, bus, and other amenities. Shopping, dining, and entertainment opportunities are easily accessible in nearby Norwood East or downtown Winnipeg.  This picturesque riverfront community is made up of mostly single family homes, though renters can take advantage of a small number of apartments along St. Mary's Road. The peaceful ambiance and safe vibe of the area makes it a popular choice for professionals who enjoy being close to downtown but don't want the noise, and congestion that can come with downtown living.  Active residents of all ages can enjoy year-round recreational activities at Norwood community centre. Baseball fields, ice-skating rinks, an outdoor pool, tennis courts and the Winnipeg Rowing Club provide additional opportunities to get fit and have fun.

column8:
Wander around downtown for the day and you'll find yourself surrounded by Winnipeg’s famed architecture, a mix of turn of the 19th century and early 20th century masonry (or, as we like to say, stone skyscrapers) and modern glass buildings. You’ll also be introduced to downtown’s culinary scene, where gourmet sandwiches, food trucks, and handcrafted cocktails are aplenty.

Above all, you’ll see the people that make this place so great - like the singer/songwriters on stage at downtown’s many live music venues, the tour guides who can introduce you to landmarks like the much-photographed oculus at the VIA Rail Station, the chefs and shop keepers of the trendy boutiques and restaurants, and our famed Golden Boy, who looks out from his perch on top of the Manitoba Legislative Building.

You can’t mention downtown without talking about Bell MTS Place, which is the home of both our NHL team, the Winnipeg Jets, and our AHL team, the Manitoba Moose. Bell MTS Place is a

column8:
You'll be staying in the heart of the Exchange District, steps away from the Red River and Stephen Juba Park which you can follow to reach the Human Rights Museum and the Forks Market with beautiful walking, ice skating & biking trails.

The Exchange District is also home to the Theatre District and from the condo you can reach the Centennial Concert Hall, and The Museum of Man and Nature within 2 minutes by foot.

There are plenty of trendy, and much loved Winnipeg eateries, local pubs and boutiques within a 15 minute walk. Check out our guidebook for our personal favorites!

You'll also be in the perfect location to partake in our City's many festivals including The Winnipeg Jazz Festival and the Winnipeg Fringe Festival or the frequent programming, events and live music held at Old Market Square all summer long.
